SIMPLE: electrotype
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Electrotype
<hw>E*lec"tro*type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Electro-</ets> + <ets>-type</ets>.]</ety> <def>A facsimile
plate made by electrotypy for use in printing; also, an impression or
print from such plate. Also used adjectively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The face of an <xex>electrotype</xex> consists of a
shell of copper, silver, or the like, produced by the action of an
electrical current upon a plate of metal and a wax mold suspended in an
acid bath and connected with opposite poles of the battery. It is backed
up with a solid filling of type metal.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Electrotype</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Electrotype
<hw>E*lec"tro*type</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Electrotyped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Electrotyping</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To
make facsimile plates of by the electrotype process; <as>as, to
<ex>electrotype</ex> a page of type, a book, etc.</as> See
<er>Electrotype</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Electrotyper</ent>⟦br⟧
